','image/jpeg',0),(261,1,'2020-10-05 09:17:00','2020-10-05 07:17:00','','img_encart1','','inherit','open','closed','','img_encart1','','','2020-10-05 09:17:00','2020-10-05 07:17:00','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/img_encart1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(263,1,'2020-10-05 09:17:28','2020-10-05 07:17:28','','img_encart2','','inherit','open','closed','','img_encart2','','','2020-10-05 09:17:28','2020-10-05 07:17:28','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/img_encart2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(265,1,'2020-10-05 09:18:31','2020-10-05 07:18:31','','img_encart4','','inherit','open','closed','','img_encart4','','','2020-10-05 09:18:31','2020-10-05 07:18:31','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/img_encart4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(269,1,'2020-10-05 09:46:03','2020-10-05 07:46:03','Atelier de restitution de l’étude de document cadre de l’éducation financière de Madagascar: mission confiée au Consortium Consulting Plus (représenté par Hery Andriamialijaona )  & Fideco (représenté par Charlot Razakaharivelo ) par le @Projet d\'Inclusion Financière de Madagascar PIFM / Banque mondiale ). ','Consulting Plus Madagascar','','publish','closed','closed','','mot-de-bienvenue','','','2022-02-14 14:29:49','2022-02-14 13:29:49','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?post_type=accueil&#038;p=269',0,'accueil','',0),(270,1,'2020-10-05 09:46:03','2020-10-05 07:46:03','Le moins que l’on puisse dire, c’est que la majorité des ménages malgaches éprouve bien de difficultés à faire face à leurs engagements financiers. Ainsi, 55% des adultes malgaches reconnaissent avoir des difficultés à tenir leurs engagements financiers, et 23% avec encore plus de difficultés ; soit quatre adultes sur cinq ou 78% sont en situation de difficultés chroniques.','Mot de bienvenue','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 09:46:03','2020-10-05 07:46:03','',269,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(271,1,'2020-10-05 09:46:50','2020-10-05 07:46:50','L’histoire de la Microfinance à Madagascar comporte trois périodes distinctes : avant 1990, de 1990 à 1996 et de 1996 à nos jours. Ainsi, l’origine de la MicroFinance à Madagascar remonte à plus d’une vingtaine d’années. Les défaillances du système bancaire en milieu rural ont favorisé la création des Institutions de MicroFinance (IMFs) à partir de 1990 à Madagascar.','Mot de bienvenue','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 09:46:50','2020-10-05 07:46:50','',269,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(272,1,'2020-10-05 09:52:49','2020-10-05 07:52:49','The history of Microfinance in Madagascar has three distinct periods: before 1990, from 1990 to 1996 and from 1996 to the present day. Thus, the origin of MicroFinance in Madagascar dates back more than twenty years. The failures of the banking system in rural areas encouraged the creation of MicroFinance Institutions (MFIs) from 1990 in Madagascar.','welcome','','publish','closed','closed','','welcome','','','2020-10-05 09:52:49','2020-10-05 07:52:49','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?post_type=accueil&#038;p=272',0,'accueil','',0),(273,1,'2020-10-05 09:52:49','2020-10-05 07:52:49','The history of Microfinance in Madagascar has three distinct periods: before 1990, from 1990 to 1996 and from 1996 to the present day. Thus, the origin of MicroFinance in Madagascar dates back more than twenty years. The failures of the banking system in rural areas encouraged the creation of MicroFinance Institutions (MFIs) from 1990 in Madagascar.','welcome','','inherit','closed','closed','','272-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 09:52:49','2020-10-05 07:52:49','',272,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/272-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(274,1,'2020-10-05 09:53:54','2020-10-05 07:53:54','The least that can be said is that the majority of Malagasy households find it very difficult to meet their financial commitments. Thus, 55% of Malagasy adults admit having difficulties in meeting their financial commitments, and 23% with even more difficulties; or four out of five adults or 78% have chronic difficulties.','Financial Education','','publish','closed','closed','','financial-education','','','2020-10-05 09:53:54','2020-10-05 07:53:54','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?post_type=documentation&#038;p=274',0,'documentation','',0),(275,1,'2020-10-05 09:53:54','2020-10-05 07:53:54','The least that can be said is that the majority of Malagasy households find it very difficult to meet their financial commitments. Thus, 55% of Malagasy adults admit having difficulties in meeting their financial commitments, and 23% with even more difficulties; or four out of five adults or 78% have chronic difficulties.','Financial Education','','inherit','closed','closed','','274-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 09:53:54','2020-10-05 07:53:54','',274,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/274-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(276,1,'2020-10-05 09:55:01','2020-10-05 07:55:01','The survey reveals that 12% of Malagasy adults are banked while 26% are affiliated with formal non-banking institutions, such as microfinance institutions or others. The other side of the coin, according to this consumer survey, is that 41% of Malagasy adults are financially excluded. This term refers to those who do not use any formal or informal financial product or service to manage their financial life.\r\n\r\nIn terms of location, 26% of adults in urban areas are banked compared to only 7% in rural areas. Financial exclusion is very important in rural areas, affecting 46% of adults compared to 31% in urban areas. And 42% of adult men are financially excluded, a figure that approximates financially excluded women which is 41% of Malagasy adult women. The informal sector reigns supreme in rural areas, affecting nearly 35% of Malagasy adults, compared to 15% in the cities.\r\n\r\nComparing the figures with other SADC countries is not at all to the Big Island\'s advantage. The banking situation of Malagasy adults (12% of adults) is only comparable to that of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) in 2014 (12%), against 78% in South Africa in 2015, and 85 % in Mauritius in 2014 pushing it to the first place of the countries of this regional community. These figures are provided by the same FinScope survey carried out in each of these countries. Thus, only 10% of adults are financially excluded in Mauritius in 2014, 13% in South Africa in 2015. But it is Mozambique which is at the top of the ranking of SADC countries in terms of financial exclusion in 2014. since it affects nearly 60% of adults there, followed by the DRC with an exclusion rate of 52%, if the banking rates are respectively 20% in Mozambique and 12% in the DRC. Among the SADC countries surveyed, only Madagascar recorded a relatively high rate of informal use (30%) followed by Zambia (21%). In Mauritius, this kind of recourse concerns only 2% of adults, against 3% for South Africa.','Financial inclusion','','publish','closed','closed','','financial-inclusion','','','2020-10-05 09:55:01','2020-10-05 07:55:01','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?post_type=documentation&#038;p=276',0,'documentation','',0),(277,1,'2020-10-05 09:55:01','2020-10-05 07:55:01','The survey reveals that 12% of Malagasy adults are banked while 26% are affiliated with formal non-banking institutions, such as microfinance institutions or others. The other side of the coin, according to this consumer survey, is that 41% of Malagasy adults are financially excluded. This term refers to those who do not use any formal or informal financial product or service to manage their financial life.\r\n\r\nIn terms of location, 26% of adults in urban areas are banked compared to only 7% in rural areas. Financial exclusion is very important in rural areas, a