as the general organization of his Ministry\n\nOn the proposal of the Director General of the Treasury,\n\nSTOPPED .\n\nArticle 1 - As of January 01, 2017, the expenditure of public bodies (State, Decentralized Territorial Collectivities, National and Local Public Establishments) for the benefit of a contractor, in particular a service provider and a supplier, natural or legal person, must be paid by transfer to the beneficiary\'s account opened at the level of a banking or financial institution.\n\nArticle 2 - From January 01, 2017, in localities served by banking or financial institutions, debts for a monthly amount exceeding six hundred thousand Ariary (Ar 600,000.00) for the benefit of civil servants, non supervised, contractual agents and pensioners, such as pay and pension, balance and pension accessories, reimbursement of medical expenses and other reimbursements of expenses in an amount exceeding six hundred thousand Ariary (Ar 600,000.00 ), must be paid by bank transfer to the beneficiary\'s account.\n\nFor debts below six hundred thousand Ariary (Ar 600,000.00), and for agents residing in localities not served by the network of banking and financial establishments, payment in cash is authorized.\n\nArticle 3 - May be paid in cash, study grants and pre-wages for civil servants and / or students, FRAM allowances as well as external mission allowances and internal mission allowances until the intervention of specific provisions. concerning.\n\nArticle 4 - All previous provisions contrary to those of this Decree are and remain abrogated, in particular those prescribed by Decree n0 9999/2000 of September 15, 2000 amending certain provisions of Decree n02087/98 of March 20, 1998 laying down the modalities of payment of public expenditure.\n\nArticle 5 - This decree will be published in the Official Journal of the Republic of Madagascar and communicated wherever needed.\n\nAntananarivo, December 26, 2016','Arrêté','','publish','closed','closed','','arrete-2','','','2020-10-08 08:25:19','2020-10-08 06:25:19','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=327',0,'page','',0),(328,1,'2020-10-05 10:44:51','2020-10-05 08:44:51','','Arrêté','','inherit','closed','closed','','327-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:44:51','2020-10-05 08:44:51','',327,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/327-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(329,1,'2020-10-05 10:45:19','2020-10-05 08:45:19','','Communicated','','publish','closed','closed','','communicated','','','2020-10-05 10:45:21','2020-10-05 08:45:21','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=329',0,'page','',0),(330,1,'2020-10-05 10:45:19','2020-10-05 08:45:19','','Communicated','','inherit','closed','closed','','329-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:45:19','2020-10-05 08:45:19','',329,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/329-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(331,1,'2020-10-05 10:47:35','2020-10-05 08:47:35','','Decrees','','publish','closed','closed','','decrees','','','2020-10-05 10:47:37','2020-10-05 08:47:37','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=331',0,'page','',0),(332,1,'2020-10-05 10:47:35','2020-10-05 08:47:35','','Decrees','','inherit','closed','closed','','331-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:47:35','2020-10-05 08:47:35','',331,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/331-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(333,1,'2020-10-05 10:47:59','2020-10-05 08:47:59','FinScope: Madagascar in figures\n\nThe Finscope consumer survey, the official results of which were just presented on Friday 11 November 2016 at the Hotel Ibis Ankorondrano, enabled certain aspects of the realities of the Big Island to be identified.\n\nMadagascar is estimated to have 11 million adults over 18, of which 41% are 30 and under. 48% of these adults are men while 52% are female. Only 27% of this adult population live in cities, compared to 73% of rural people.\n\nAgriculture and infrastructure\n\n71% of Malagasy households are involved in agriculture. For this, 18% of said households consume all their produce, while only 9% practice agriculture exclusively for commercial purposes. This situation is generally due to the small size of the land to be cultivated, the lack of control or the lack of water as well as the low yield of crops. The vast majority of these households, 73%, practice mixed farming, which consists of consuming part of their produce while the other part is intended for sale.\n\nThe causes of the problems encountered by Malagasy farmers are multiple, including drought, natural disasters destroying crops or obstructing the irrigation canals by silting up, but also the lack of tools and equipment and the scarcity of improved seeds. In addition, most farmers do not own their land.\n\nIn fact, only 31% of farming households have a document, such as the title deed or cadastre, of the land they cultivate. It should also be noted that nearly 49% of farming households own less than one are of land and only less than 2% have more than five ares.\n\nAs regards the financing rates for agricultural inputs, they are quite disparate. This survey has, for example, made it possible to establish that 31% of Malagasy farming households draw the source of funding for inputs into livestock (sale of livestock), 21% through the sale of agricultural production, while only 1% have recourse to formal credit from microfinance institutions or other financial institutions, compared to 6% who rely on their friends or families.\n\n68% of Malagasy households in urban areas have access to running water compared to 17% of rural people, or a total of 31% of households in Madagascar. As for electricity, 72% of city dwellers have it and only 16% of rural dwellers. The main source of electricity remains the company JIRAMA for 94% of these households in urban areas, and 76% of rural households among the 16%. In terms of solar panels, only 3% of urban households use them as a source of electricity, compared to 16% in rural areas. But quite unique, 3% of city dwellers have their neighbors as electricity suppliers, and 2% in rural areas.\n\nFinancial Education\n\nThe least that can be said is that the majority of Malagasy households find it very difficult to meet their financial commitments. Thus, 55% of Malagasy adults admit having difficulties in meeting their financial commitments, and 23% with even more difficulties; or four out of five adults or 78% have chronic difficulties.\n\nFaced with this situation, 58% of Malagasy adults believe they need more information on managing their income. Thus, 46% wish to learn to budget and, the same rate (46%) is also recorded for those who would like to learn to invest. 42% want to find the answer to the questions: \"How to save? \"And\" How to get a loan? \". Also, financial education is becoming an absolute necessity for the general population, in order to enable them to better manage their financial life.\n\nIn terms of education, the popular belief that the urban population is educated rather than the rural population is not fully verified. Thus, two in three rural adults were able to receive primary education, while the ratio would be one in three adults in urban areas. In total, 57% of adults have completed primary education or less. And it turns out that the level of education definitely has an impact on the financial education of individuals, as formal education improves their math and comprehension skills. Skills which also provide some knowledge of formal financial products and services, their operation, but also knowledge of certain financial terms. And this education landscape makes it possible to know that Malagasy adults prioritize education over other necessary and vital things in life, such as housing or leisure.\n\nPoor financial education would increase the rate of use of informal financial products. Thus, adults weakly inst','FINSCOPE surveys','','publish','closed','closed','','finscope-surveys','','','2020-10-08 08:27:48','2020-10-08 06:27:48','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=333',0,'page','',0),(334,1,'2020-10-05 10:47:59','2020-10-05 08:47:59','','FINSCOPE surveys','','inherit','closed','closed','','333-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:47:59','2020-10-05 08:47:59','',333,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/333-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(335,1,'2020-10-05 10:48:50','2020-10-05 08:48:50','','Training','','publish','closed','closed','','training','','','2020-10-05 10:48:52','2020-10-05 08:48:52','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=335',0,'page','',0),(336,1,'2020-10-05 10:48:50','2020-10-05 08:48:50','','Training','','inherit','closed','closed','','335-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:48:50','2020-10-05 08:48:50','',335,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/335-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(337,1,'2020-10-05 10:49:20','2020-10-05 08:49:20','<h2>History of financial inclusion in Madagascar</h2>\r\n<p>\r\nThree main periods have marked the history of financial inclusion in Madagascar:\r\n<ul >\r\n<li> The microcredit era</li>\r\n<li> The microfinance era</li>\r\n<li> The financial inclusion era </li>\r\nThe microcredit era (pre-1990)\r\nPrior to 1990, the former Bankin\'ny Tantsaha Mpamokatra or BTM, currently known as BOA Madagascar, was involved in granting credit to small-scale farmers. At that time, it was called agricultural microcredit.\r\nThe era of microfinance (from 1990)\r\nIn the 1990s, the advent of \"microfinance\" made its appearance in Madagascar. This era was marked by two main phases:\r\n<li> From 1990 to 1996: the first microfinance institutions emerged, including \r\n\r\n	<ul class=\"child\">\r\n		<li> the Savings and Self-managed Credit Association, Association d\'Epargne et de Crédit Autogérés - AECA Marovoay in 1990,</li>\r\n		<li> the Investment Company for the Promotion of Enterprises, Société d\'Investissement pour la Promotion des Entreprises à Madagascar - SIPEM in 1990</li>\r\n		<li> the Savings Cashier and Mutual Credits, Caisse d\'Epargne et de Crédit Mutuels - CECAM Vakinankaratra in 1993</li>\r\n		<li> Vola Mahasoa Toliary in 1993,</li>\r\n		<li> the Ombona Tahiry Ifampisamborana Vola - OTIV Toamasina and Alaotra Mangoro in 1994</li>\r\n		<li> the Financial Development Agency - ADEFI in 1995 (currently ACEP Madagascar)</li>\r\n		<li> and Tahiry Ifampisamborana Vola - TIAVO Fianarantsoa</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li> From 1996 onwards: development and growth phase of Microfinance Institutions</li>\r\n<li> 1999: Creation of the AGEPMF Microfinance Project Execution Agency (Government project financed by the World Bank) and establishment of a microfinance sector coordination unit within the Ministry of Finance</li>\r\n<li> September 2003: Completion of a diagnostic study of the microfinance sector in Madagascar in technical and financial partnership with the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and the United Nations Capital Development Fund (UNCDF).</li>\r\n<li> December 2003: Setting up of the National Coordination of Microfinance - CNMF within the General Directorate of the Treasury </li>\r\n<li> February 2004: Establishment of the MicroFinance Working Group to prepare the first National MicroFinance Strategy - SNMF</li>\r\n<li> April 2004: Workshop to validate the National Microfinance Strategy</li>\r\n<li> June 2004: Approval by the Government of the National Microfinance Strategy - SNMF 2004-2009</li>\r\n<li> October 2004: Appointment of the members of the Steering Committee for the implementation of the National Microfinance Strategy</li>\r\n<li> March 2005: First Round Table of Donors of the microfinance sector</li>\r\n<li> September 2005: Publication of the new microfinance law N° 2005-016</li>\r\n<li> February 2007 : \r\n	<ul class=\"child\">\r\n			<li>Publication of the application decrees 2007-012 legal forms and 2007-013 minimum capital related to the law N° 2005-016 of microfinance</li>\r\n			<li>Official launch of the United Nations Blue Book in Madagascar: \"Building inclusive financial sectors</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li> September - October 2007 :\r\n	<ul class=\"child\">\r\n			<li>Mid-term evaluation of the National Microfinance Strategy - SNMF 2004-2009</li>\r\n			<li>Validation workshop of the mid-term evaluation and elaboration of the National Microfinance Strategy SNMF 2008-2012 aligned with the visions of the Madagascar Action Plan - MAP</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li> April 2008: Budgeting of the SNMF 2008-2012 Action Plan</li>\r\n<li> November 2008: Government approval of the SNMF 2008-2012</li>\r\n\r\nThe era of inclusive finance - financial inclusion (from 2012)\r\nThis period was marked by the transition from microfinance to inclusive finance following the final evaluation of the implementation of the National Microfinance Strategy - SNMF 2008-2012.\r\n<li> June 2012: Final evaluation of the SNMF 2008-2012 and development of the National Strategy for Inclusive Finance - SNFI 2013-2017</li>\r\n<li> July 2015: Official launch of the \"Making Access to Financial Services Possible -MAP\" Initiative.</li>\r\n<li> 2015-2016: Conducting the FinScope Consumer Survey to measure adults\' levels of access to financial services, their uses, their quality.</li>\r\n<li> March 2016: First participation of Madagascar in the celebration of the Global Money Week.</li>\r\n<li> November 2016: Restitution and publication of the results of the FinScope Madagascar Survey</li>\r\n<li> 2017: Completion of the Diagnostic of the financial services offer and development of the roadmap for financial inclusion in Madagascar.</li>\r\n<li> February 2017: The use of electronic money is officially recognized with Law 2016-056 of February 2, 2017. </li>\r\n<li> December 2017: The microfinance sector is now governed by a new law: law 2017-026 of December 7, 2017</li>\r\n\r\n<li> 2016 : PPBDM project </li>\r\n<li> February 2018 : Promulgation of Law 2017-045 of February 15, 2018 governing the activity and control of credit information bureaus. </li>\r\n<li> July 2018: 1st Prize awarded to Madagascar for the Africa Zone as part of the celebration of the Global Money Week - Inclusion Awards</li>\r\n<li> October 2018: Official launch of the Madagascar Financial Inclusion Project (MFIP)</li>\r\n<li> November 2018: Official launch of the Madagascar National Strategy for Financial Inclusion (SNIM 2018-2022)</li>\r\n<li> December 2019: Completion of the Diagnostic Study on the state of financial education in Madagascar</li>\r\n<li> September 2020: The banking sector is now governed by a new law: law 2020-011 of September 1, 2020. </li>\r\n<li> September 2020: The insurance sector is now governed by a new law: Law 2020-005 of September 1, 2020.</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n','History of financial inclusion in Madagascar','','publish','closed','closed','','history-of-microfinance-towards-financial-inclusion','','','2021-07-13 09:58:17','2021-07-13 07:58:17','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=337',0,'page','',0),(338,1,'2020-10-05 10:49:20','2020-10-05 08:49:20','','History of microfinance towards financial inclusion','','inherit','closed','closed','','337-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:49:20','2020-10-05 08:49:20','',337,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/337-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(339,1,'2020-10-05 10:49:43','2020-10-05 08:49:43','','Indicators of financial inclusion in Madagascar','','publish','closed','closed','','indicators-of-financial-inclusion-in-madagascar','','','2020-10-05 10:49:46','2020-10-05 08:49:46','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=339',0,'page','',0),(340,1,'2020-10-05 10:49:43','2020-10-05 08:49:43','','Indicators of financial inclusion in Madagascar','','inherit','closed','closed','','339-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:49:43','2020-10-05 08:49:43','',339,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/339-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(341,1,'2020-10-05 10:50:18','2020-10-05 08:50:18','','Instruction','','publish','closed','closed','','instruction-2','','','2020-10-05 10:50:21','2020-10-05 08:50:21','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=341',0,'page','',0),(342,1,'2020-10-05 10:50:18','2020-10-05 08:50:18','','Instruction','','inherit','closed','closed','','341-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:50:18','2020-10-05 08:50:18','',341,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/341-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(343,1,'2020-10-05 10:52:00','2020-10-05 08:52:00','','Geographical location','','publish','closed','closed','','geographical-location','','','2020-10-16 13:42:44','2020-10-16 11:42:44','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=343',0,'page','',0),(344,1,'2020-10-05 10:52:00','2020-10-05 08:52:00','','Geographical location','','inherit','closed','closed','','343-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:52:00','2020-10-05 08:52:00','',343,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/343-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(345,1,'2020-10-05 10:52:30','2020-10-05 08:52:30','COMMON LEGISLATIVE FRAMEWORK\n\nRegulation of Credit Institutions\n\nLaw No. 95-030 of February 22, 1996 relating to\n\nLEGISLATIVE FRAMEWORK SPECIFIC TO MICROFINANCE\n\nLaw No. 2005-016 of September 29, 2005 on\n\nDecree No. 2007-012 fixing the forms\n\nDecree No. 2007-013 fixing','Law','','publish','closed','closed','','law','','','2020-10-08 08:19:29','2020-10-08 06:19:29','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=345',0,'page','',0),(346,1,'2020-10-05 10:52:30','2020-10-05 08:52:30','','Law','','inherit','closed','closed','','345-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:52:30','2020-10-05 08:52:30','',345,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/345-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(347,1,'2020-10-05 10:53:14','2020-10-05 08:53:14','The actors who intervene for the sector at the macro level are:\n-\n\n<strong> The supervisory authority: </strong>\n\nThe Banking and Financial Supervision Commission (CSBF) is the supervisory authority for credit institutions.\nIt is responsible for:\n<ol>\n 	<li> ensure the proper functioning of credit institutions,</li>\n 	<li> verify that credit institutions comply with the provisions applicable to them, and</li>\n 	<li> sanction the breaches noted.</li>\n</ol>\nIt examines, in particular, the operating conditions of credit institutions, ensures the quality of their financial situation and monitors compliance with the rules of good conduct of the profession.\n\nThe CSBF also issues authorizations to carry out microfinance activities.\n\n<strong> The Steering Committee for the implementation of the National MicroFinance Strategy </strong>\n\nThe Steering Committee was set up in October 2004. It is made up of representatives of the State, the Professional Association of Microfinance Institutions, the Professional Association of Banks and Technical and Financial Partners. He is in charge of monitoring the Strategy Action Plan, proposing adaptation measures, leading thematic discussions.\n\nThe mandate of the members of the Steering Committee for the implementation of the National MicroFinance Strategy is one year renewable by ministerial decision.\n\nGiven the context of the crisis since 2009, the Steering Committee for the implementation of the SNMF 2008-2012 could not function as it should.\n\n<strong> Technical and Financial Partners: </strong>\n\nThe TFPs provide financing and technical support in the implementation of the National Microfinance Strategy (SNMF), either at the level of MFIs, CNMF, Professional Association, CSBF, or in the establishment of \'a common multi-donor fund. We can cite :\n<ol>\n 	<li> <a title=\"AFD website\" href=\"http://www.afd.fr/jahia/Jahia/home/pays-d-intervention-afd/afrique-sub-saharienne/pays-afrique / madagascar\" target=\" _ blank \" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> French Development Agency AFD </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"BAD website\" href=\"http://www.afdb.org/en/countries/southern-africa/madagascar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> African Development Bank AfDB <!-- a--> </a></li>\n<a title=\"BAD website\" href=\"http://www.afdb.org/en/countries/southern-africa/madagascar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n</a>\n 	<li><a title=\"BAD website\" href=\"http://www.afdb.org/en/countries/southern-africa/madagascar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> </a><a title=\"World Bank site\" href=\"http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/ACCUEILEXTN/PAYSEXTN/AFRICAINFRENCHEXT/MADAGASCARINFRENCHEXTN/0,,menuPK:469036~pagePK:141159~ piPK: 55000052 ~ theSitePK: 468974,00.html\" target=\" _ blank \" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> World Bank </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site du CARE\" href=\"http://www.care.mg/\"> CARE INTERNATIONAL Madagascar </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site du CRS Madagascar\" href=\"http://crs.org/Madagascar/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Catholic Relief Services Madagascar CRS </a></li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.uncdf.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> United Nations Equipment Fund (UNCDF) </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"IFAD website\" href=\"http://www.capfida.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> IFAD International Fund for Agricultural Development </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site de l\'Intercooperation Suisse Madagascar\" href=\"http://www.intercooperation-mg.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Intercooperation Suisse Madagascar </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"JICA website\" href=\"http://www.jica.go.jp/madagascar/english/index.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Japan International Cooperation Agency JICA </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site KFW\" href=\"http://www.kfw-entwicklungsbank.de/EN_Home/LocalPresence/Sub-Sahara62/Office_Madagascar/index.jsp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> KFW <!-- a --> </a></li>\n<a title=\"Site KFW\" href=\"http://www.kfw-entwicklungsbank.de/EN_Home/LocalPresence/Sub-Sahara62/Office_Madagascar/index.jsp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n</a>\n 	<li><a title=\"Site KFW\" href=\"http://www.kfw-entwicklungsbank.de/EN_Home/LocalPresence/Sub-Sahara62/Office_Madagascar/index.jsp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> </a><a title=\"OIT Site\" href=\"http://www.ilo.org/public/french/region/afpro/antananarivo/index.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> International Organization of ILO work </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"UNDP website\" href=\"http://www.snu.mg/pnud/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> United Nations Development Program UNDP </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site of the European Union\" href=\"http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/madagascar/index_en.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> European Union EU </a> &lt; / li&gt;</li>\n 	<li> <a title=\" USAID Madagascar website\" href=\"http://www.usaid.gov/mg/en/index.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> United States Agency for International Development USAID Madagascar </a></li>\n</ol>\n<strong> Ministries and related organizations\n</strong>\n\nThe supervision of the microfinance sector is provided by the <a title=\"Site of the MEFB\" href=\"http://www.mefb.gov.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Ministry of Finance and Budget <!-- a-->. Many MFIs operate in rural areas and the </a><a title=\"Site of the Ministry of Agriculture\" href=\"http://www.agriculture.gov.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Ministry of Agriculture </a> also plays a large role in the development of rural finance.\n\nThe National Coordination of Inclusive Finance (CNFI) is administratively attached to the Directorate of Financial Operations (DOF) within the General Directorate of the Treasury (DGT). The DGT is hierarchically attached to the General Secretariat of the Ministry of Finance and Budget','Macro level','','publish','closed','closed','','macro-level','','','2020-10-08 08:09:57','2020-10-08 06:09:57','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=347',0,'page','',0),(348,1,'2020-10-05 10:53:14','2020-10-05 08:53:14','','Macro level','','inherit','closed','closed','','347-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:53:14','2020-10-05 08:53:14','',347,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/347-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(349,1,'2020-10-05 10:53:37','2020-10-05 08:53:37','At the meso level, there are support structures for the sector such as:\n\n<strong> Program projects intervening in the sector: </strong>\n\nSeveral projects and programs with a microfinance component or component work for the sector, including: <strong>\n</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li> Muensingen collaboration program in Madagascar</li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"PPRR website\" href=\"http://www.pprr.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Rural Income Promotion Program (PPRR) </a></li>\n 	<li> Rural Development Support Program (PSDR)</li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site du PROSPERER\" href=\"http://www.prosperer.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Support program for rural micro-enterprise poles and regional economies (PROSPERER) &lt; / a&gt; </a></li>\n<a title=\"Site du PROSPERER\" href=\"http://www.prosperer.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">\n 	<li> Support Program for Inclusive Finance in Madagascar (PAFIM)</li>\n 	<li> Financial Services Support Program (PASEF)</li>\n</a>\n 	<li><a title=\"Site du PROSPERER\" href=\"http://www.prosperer.mg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> </a><a title=\"Site du SNU\" href=\"http://www.snu.mg/new/sites/pnud\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Sustainable Livelihoods and Poverty Reduction Program (MSDLCP) </a></li>\n 	<li> <a title=\"Site de l\'Intercooperation\" href=\"http://www.intercooperation-mg.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> Program \"Sahan\'Asa Hampandrosoana ny eny Ambanivohitra\" (SAHA III) </a></li>\n 	<li> Manombo perimeter rehabilitation project (PRPIM)</li>\n 	<li> Support project for the fishing communities of Tulear (PACP)</li>\n 	<li> Menabe and Melaky Development Support Project (AD2M)</li>\n 	<li> Rary Vola Project</li>\n</ol>\n<strong> Professional Association of Microfinance Institutions: </strong>\n\nAccording to the provisions of Law 2005-016 of September 29, 2005, the APIMF is a civil association recognized as being of public utility (article 61).\nIts missions are to:\n<ol>\n 	<li> ensure the representation of microfinance institutions and the defense of professional interests with the Government, with professional institutions, credit establishments or institutions and organizations</li>\n 	<li> international. to encourage cooperation between microfinance institutions involved in the development of microfinance activities</li>\n</ol>\nAlso, all microfinance institutions that have obtained a license to practice from the CSBF are required to join this professional association. The terms of membership are set by the association\'s internal regulations.\n\nAccording to article 14 of its statute, the organs of the Association are:\n\n- the general Assembly\n- the Supervisory Board\n- board of directors\n- the Ethics Committee\n- the General Secretariat\n\nThe constitutive assembly of the association took place on July 02, 2011.\n\n<strong> Service providers </strong>\n\nBelow is a non-exhaustive list of service providers who have experience in the field of microfinance. Their areas of intervention vary between: market research, communication, information system, audit and accounting expertise, ...\n<ol>\n 	<li> ALTEC</li>\n 	<li> MADAGASCAR</li>\n 	<li> AMBER ASSOCIATES</li>\n 	<li> Cabinet MPANAZAVA</li>\n 	<li> Cabinet</li>\n 	<li> RASOANAIVO</li>\n 	<li> CGA</li>\n 	<li> CONSULTING PLUS</li>\n 	<li> EUROGROUP</li>\n 	<li> FIDEV CONSEIL</li>\n 	<li> FTHM TIPS</li>\n 	<li> GAMA CONSULT</li>\n 	<li> MAZARS</li>\n 	<li> FIVOARANA</li>\n 	<li> ORCHID SYSTEM</li>\n 	<li> PLANET FINANCE Madagascar</li>\n</ol>','Meso Level','','publish','closed','closed','','meso-level','','','2020-10-08 08:11:17','2020-10-08 06:11:17','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=349',0,'page','',0),(350,1,'2020-10-05 10:53:37','2020-10-05 08:53:37','','Meso Level','','inherit','closed','closed','','349-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:53:37','2020-10-05 08:53:37','',349,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/349-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2020-10-05 10:54:03','2020-10-05 08:54:03','Micro Level Actors\nCredit institutions carrying out microfinance activities are the hard core of the microfinance sector. We can distinguish :\n\nFinancial institutions\nTerritorial banks\nMicrofinance institutions\n\nFinancial institutions\nA financial institution operates in the microfinance sector. This is the REGIONAL FINANCIAL INSTITUTION OF ANOSY (IFRA)\n\nTerritorial banks\nCurrently, three territorial banks carry out microfinance activities, namely:','Micro level','','publish','closed','closed','','micro-level','','','2020-10-08 08:14:46','2020-10-08 06:14:46','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=351',0,'page','',0),(352,1,'2020-10-05 10:54:03','2020-10-05 08:54:03','','Micro level','','inherit','closed','closed','','351-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:54:03','2020-10-05 08:54:03','',351,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(353,1,'2020-10-05 10:54:58','2020-10-05 08:54:58','[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"CHALLENGE UNCDF\" class=\"blocToggleone\" show=\"show\"]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center; font-weight: bold;\">Call for Innovators in Africa</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center; font-weight: bold;\">Digital innovations for ODD acceleration</p>\r\nAs part of itsstrategy for the development of inclusive digital economies, UNCDF isorganizing a regional challenge \"Digital Innovations\r\nfor AcceleratingSustainableDevelopment Goals (SDGs)\" to identify high-impact, inclusive innovations thatoffer a real opportunity to accelerate the Agenda\r\n2030 for sustainabledevelopment for the populations of the following 10 countries: Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Comoros, Gabon, Madagascar, Mali, Mauritania,\r\nNiger and Senegal. This challenge revolvesaround the threepillars of intervention of the UNCDF strategy, which aspires to \"Leave no one behind in the digital age\".\r\n\r\nUNCDF will use a selection process in 2 waves in November 2020 and April 2021:\r\n\r\nFor more information on this call, pleasevisit the followinglink:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.uncdf.org/article/6286/rfa-challenge-rgional-innovations-numriques-pour-lacclration-des-objectifs-de-dveloppement-durable\">https://www.uncdf.org/article/6286/rfa-challenge-rgional-innovations-numriques-pour-lacclration-des-objectifs-de-dveloppement-durable</a>\r\n\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"Madagascar Financial Inclusion Project PIFM\"]\r\n\r\nThe Malagasy Governmentsigned a Credit Agreement worth 31,600,000 DTS, equivalent to US$45,000,000, with the International Development Association (IDA) - World Bank to finance the Madagascar Financial Inclusion Project (PIFM - 6189 MG) on April 19, 2018. The projectwasimplemented on September 28, 2018. The closing date of the projectisscheduled for July 31, 2022.\r\n\r\nThe Project Development Objective (PDP) is to \"promote the financial inclusion of individuals and MSMEs in Madagascar\" notablybyincreasing the use of transaction accounts and access to credit for MSMEs.\r\n\r\nThe Project isimplementedthrough four (4) main components: (i) digitization of payments to increase the use of transaction accounts; (ii) access to credit for micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs); (iii) project management and impact assessment; and (iv) emergency responsecontingency.\r\n\r\nComponent 1 supports the digitization of payments to increase the use of transaction accounts, through :\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>digitization of governmentpaymentsthrough the payment of teachers\' salaries and scholarships and sometaxrevenues;</li>\r\n 	<li>digitization of microfinance institutions (MFIs) through the integration of MFIs\' mobile services and the implementation of a shared MFI information and management system (MIS); and</li>\r\n 	<li>creation of an environmentconducive to the increased use of transaction accountsthrough the modernization of paymentsystems infrastructure and a financialeducationcampaign.\r\nComponent 2 supports access to credit for MSMEsthrough :</li>\r\n 	<li>Support for more credit provision to MSMEs by increasing the capital of partial credit portfolio guaranteefunds and an innovation fund for FINTECH solutions;</li>\r\n 	<li>Supportingloan applications by setting up enterprisedevelopment services (EDS) for MSMEs and expanding MFI branches to underservedareas; and</li>\r\n 	<li>Creating an enablingenvironment for access to credit for MSMEsthrough the establishment of an electronicregistry of centralizedguarantees and the improvement of the consumer protection framework.\r\nComponent 3 will finance the operating costs and the impact study of the component on increasing the use of transaction accountsthroughgovernmentpayments.\r\nComponent 4 willallow the rapidreallocation of projectfunds in the event of a natural or man-made disaster or crisiscausing or likely to cause an imminent major negativeeconomic and/or social impact.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n\r\n[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"PROJECT TO PROMOTE DISTANCE BANKING IN MADAGASCAR (PPBDM)\"]\r\n\r\n<p>The Malagasy Government has received a grant of 2,000,000 Euros from the French Agency for Development (Agence Française de Développement- AFD), in accordance with the AFD Financing Agreement N°CMG 1390 01R of 16 June 2014, for the implementation of a Project for the Promotion of Distance Banking in Madagascar (Projet de Promotion de la Banque à Distance à Madagascar- PPBDM). </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Palladium (Ex-Enclude) wasrecruited as Project Management Unit (PMU) to ensure the delegatedproject management. It is in charge of the implementation of the Project. A contract on the PPBDM wassignedbetweenEnclude and the Ministry of Finance and Budget, represented by the CNFI on September 28, 2016.</p>\r\n<p>The Project\'s objective is to maximizeaccess to adaptedfinancial services, particularly for the benefit of disadvantaged populations excludedfrom the traditionalfinancial system in rural areas. The closing date of the projectisscheduled for May 2020, the deadline for disbursement of fundsisDecember 31, 2020 and the deadline for disbursement of fundsis June 30, 2021.\r\nThe specific objectives of the Project are</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>the financial inclusion strategy of one or more MFIsisoptimized in rural areas ;</li>\r\n<li>microfinance clients in rural areas have easieraccess to formalfinancial services that are adapted to theirneeds and accountablethrough distance banking; and</li>\r\n<li>CNFI isbetterequipped to carry out itscoordinatingrole in the implementation of the National Strategy for Financial Inclusion,particularly on issues related to financial inclusion in rural areas and the development of distance banking solutions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nProject activities are dividedinto 2 phases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Phase 1:Early Identification of the Project. \r\nThe objective of Phase 1 is to assess the feasibility of the distance banking solutions proposed by the MFIsthat have applied for the project. Three (03) Microfinance Institutions, namely ACEP, Société Mutualiste Malgache d\'Epargne et de Crédit - SMMEC (formerly OTIV TANA) and OTIV DIANA, have been selected and supported by the project to developa distance banking solution.</li>\r\n<li>Phase 2: Project implementation. </li>\r\nThe implementation phase issubdividedintoseveralactivities:</li>\r\n<li>Support for the implementation of the developmentstrategies of the threeMFIs\' distance bankingsolutions;</li>\r\n<li>Support for the deployment of theseremotebankingsolutions; and</li>\r\n<li>Knowledge management, capitalization of acquiredknowledge and skillstransfer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"SUPPORT PROGRAM TO RURAL MICROENTREPRISES AND REGIONAL ECONOMIES\"]\r\n\r\n<p>The Program to Support Rural Microenterprise Poles and Regional Economies (PROSPERER) is one of the major actors in the financial inclusion of individuals and micro-enterprises in rural Madagascar.\r\n</p><p>\r\nSigned on December 18, 2007 and began operating on April 28, 2008 for a period of 7 years, the Program aims to promote income increase through the consolidation and empowerment of rural microenterprises at the local and regional level. It has received two additional funding from the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) in 2013 and 2015 to bring its total cost to US$65.14 million and to extend its completion date from June 30, 2015 to December 31, 2021. </p><p>\r\nUnder the supervision of the Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Fisheries and piloted by the Ministry of Industry, Trade and Handicrafts, the Program is implemented by the Federation of Chambers of Commerce and Industry of Madagascar through its network of Regional Chambers of Commerce and Industry (CCI). It currently operates in 35 districts spread over 9 regions of Madagascar, namely Analamanga, Itasy, Bongolava, Haute Matsiatra, Vatovavy Fitovinany, Boeny, Sofia, Atsinanana and Analanjirofo. \r\nThe Program is implemented through 5 components, namely :\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Component 1: Identification and mobilization of MER (Rural MicroEnterprise), PER (Small Rural Enterprise) and structuring of inter-professions,</li>\r\n<li>Component 2: Rural microenterprise support services and vocational training,</li>\r\n<li>Component 3: Rural Finance and Risk Management,</li>\r\n<li>Component 4: Market infrastructure and structuring investments, and</li>\r\n<li>Component 5: Monitoring-evaluation, capitalization and communication.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n</p><p>As part of the promotion of financial inclusion, PROSPERER has aligned the objectives of its Component 3 \"Rural Finance and Risk Management\" with the National Microfinance Strategy from 2008 to 2012 and the National Strategies for Financial Inclusion since 2013. The objective is to promote the development of rural areas through better access to financial services adapted to their needs, in a sustainable manner and under favorable risk management conditions. \r\n\r\n</p><p>To do this, PROSPERER collaborates with three (03) Partner Financial Institutions, namely VOLA MAHASOA, ACEP Madagascar and Premiere Agence de Microfinance -PAMF), through the financial mechanisms put in place such as: \r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>(i) Rural Investment Facility (RIF) to support the access to credit of the MFIs through the availability of a sustainable refinancing fund for partner MFIs;</li>  \r\n	<li>(ii) Entrepreneurship Support Fund (ESF) to facilitate access to the first loans from the MFIs;</li>  \r\n	<li>(iii) Institutional Support Fund (ISF) to remove the constraints related to the difficulty for MFIs to access the financial products of partner MFIs; and </li>  \r\n	<li>(iv) Risk Sharing Facility (RSF) to support the risks incurred by partner MFIs in the event of non-repayment of loans granted to REMs. </li>  \r\n</ul>\r\n</p><p>PROSPERER has also developed an alternative methodology to promote access to basic financial services (savings and credit) and non-financial services (financial education) for vulnerable MERs excluded from any formal financial system through the creation of Village Groups for Community Mutual Aid ( Groupement Villageois d’Entraide Communautaire - GVEC) with a view to linking these groups with partner financial institutions.\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n\r\n[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"NETWORK OF SAVINGS GROUPS PROMOTERS IN MADAGASCAR (RPGEM)\"]\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nThe Network of Savings Group Promoters in Madagascar (Réseau des Promoteurs  des Groupes d’Epargne à Madagascar - RPGEM) is a non-profit association gathering the promoters of savings groups in Madagascar. A savings group is a group of people who choose themselves to form a savings group together and set aside money that will later be used for loans. \r\nThe RPGEM intervenes in the implementation of the strategic axis 2 of the National Strategy for Financial Inclusion of Madagascar (SNIM 2018 - 2022) to allow a better supervision and monitoring of savings groups. The latter are seen as means of facilitating access for vulnerable populations excluded from any formal financial system to basic financial services (savings and credit) and non-financial services (financial education).</p><p>\r\nFounded in 2016, the RPGEM\'s mission is to promote the implementation of quality savings group programs in Madagascar.\r\nWithin this framework, its mission is to ensure :\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> Advocacy actions with technical, administrative and financial partners on the role of savings groups in financial inclusion ;</li>\r\n<li> Capitalizing achievements and exchanges on good practices in the promotion of savings groups;</li>\r\n<li> Ensuring the commitment of promoters to the quality and respect of the principles governing savings groups; and</li>\r\n<li> Developing a frank and transparent partnership.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p><p>\r\nThe implementation of the RPGEM follows the adoption and development of savings group models by various institutions and non-governmental organizations such as USAID, Catholic Relief Services (CRS), CARE, FAA, OSDRM,  Support program to rural microentreprises and regional economies (PROgramme de Soutien aux Poles de micro-Entreprises Rurales et aux Economies Regionales- PROSPERER), the United Nations Capital Development Funds (UNCDF), etc. at the national level after the introduction of the Village Savings and Loan Associations (VSLA) methodology by CARE in Madagascar in 2006.\r\n</p><p>\r\nThe Network has a database, the SAVIX Network, to record data on savings groups. In 2019, SAVIX counted 7435 savings groups in Madagascar with 152,741 members and a high proportion of women (68.2%). The average annual savings per member is USD 39 and the total savings outstanding is USD 2.94 million.\r\n</p><p>\r\nIn 2019, the Network was strengthened through the enrollment of Private Service Provider (PSP) networks and units within the RPGEM following the completion of the CRS FARARANO Project and CARE\'s Ombona Project.\r\n</p><p>\r\nFrom the perspective of financial inclusion, various promoters are experimenting with linking savings groups with formal financial institutions. For example, the PROSPERER Program is gradually linking Village Groups of Community Mutual Aid (Groupements Villageois d’Entraide Communautaire - GVEC) with its three partner Microfinance Institutions (VOLA MAHASOA, ACEP Madagascar and PAMF) or CARE Madagascar by linking 40 VOAMAMI savings groups with the Bank Société Générale Madagasikara through the use of the Mvola mobile money account within the framework of the Ombona Project.\r\nUNCDF has opted for the development of financial innovations based on mobile financial services in order to promote the financial inclusion of savings groups located in the south of Madagascar (Anosy and Androy Regions) within the framework of the Project to Support Endogenous Mechanisms for Community Dialogue and Improve the Economic Conditions of Vulnerable Populations.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n[bloc-toogle-div titre=\"USAID - Hay Tao\"]\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n\r\nUSAID Hay Tao is a biodiversity conservation program funded by USAID and implemented by a consortium of international and national organizations (Alliance Voahary Gasy (AVG), Solidarity of Actors on Land, Solidarité des Intervenants sur le Foncier (SIF), World Resources Institute (WRI) and the Coastal Resources Center of the University of Rhode Island (URI-CRC).).Throughitsapproach, Hay Tao promotes the involvement of women and youth in community-basednaturalresource management and sustainablelivelihooddevelopmentthrough the promotion of socialentrepreneurship and conservation entrepreneurship. \r\nHay Tao aims to conserve biodiversity and securenaturalresourcesthrough the promotion of resilientlivelihoods. To achievethis goal, Hay Tao collaborateswithdifferentactorsfrom the public sector, privatesector and civil society to :\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>(i) Create a national platform for social entrepreneurship and conservation with stakeholder involvement</li>\r\n<li>(ii) Develop the reference guide on social and conservation entrepreneurship</li>\r\n<li>(iii) Developinga Model for Social and ConservationEntrepreneurship</li>\r\n<li>(iv) Set up a mechanism for a return to social and environmental issues. </li>\r\n<li>(v) Establish a legalframework for social entrepreneurship and conservation enterprise in Madagascar.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n[/bloc-toogle-div]\r\n\r\n\r\n','Ongoing project','','publish','closed','closed','','ongoing-project','','','2021-07-13 09:40:33','2021-07-13 07:40:33','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=353',0,'page','',0),(354,1,'2020-10-05 10:54:58','2020-10-05 08:54:58','','Ongoing project','','inherit','closed','closed','','353-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:54:58','2020-10-05 08:54:58','',353,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/353-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(355,1,'2020-10-05 10:55:24','2020-10-05 08:55:24','','Sector publications (Journal, Bulletin, etc.)','','publish','closed','closed','','sector-publications-journal-bulletin-etc','','','2020-10-05 10:55:26','2020-10-05 08:55:26','',0,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/?page_id=355',0,'page','',0),(356,1,'2020-10-05 10:55:24','2020-10-05 08:55:24','','Sector publications (Journal, Bulletin, etc.)','','inherit','closed','closed','','355-revision-v1','','','2020-10-05 10:55:24','2020-10-05 08:55:24','',355,'http://192.168.0.199/siteweb/CNFI/2020/10/05/355-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(357,1,'2020-10-05 10:55:48','2020-10-05 08:55:48','','Study report','','publish','closed','closed','','study-report','','','2020-10-05 10:55:50','2020